Analyzing Sneakers Price From Stockx¶

Sixiao He - DATS 6103¶

Background¶

With the Thanksgiving day and Christmas day coming, many people will buy some sneakers as presents for their friends and family, it is necessary to know the fluctuation of the price which influenced by several factors.This project is to help you to get your favorite shoes with suitable price.

Description from Stockx:¶

Description from StockX: The data consists of a random sample of all Off-White x Nike and Yeezy 350 sales from between 9/1/2017 and 2/13/2019. There are 99,956 total sales in the data set; 27,794 Off-White sales, and 72,162 Yeezy sales. And the data only consists of U.S. sales only.

# Change 'release date' to the datetime
df['Release Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Release Date'], format='%m/%d/%y')
In [11]:
# Remove - from sneaker name
df['Sneaker Name'] = df['Sneaker Name'].apply(lambda x: x.replace('-', ' '))
In [12]:
# Remove $ and comma from sale price
df['Sale Price'] = df['Sale Price'].apply(lambda x: x.replace('$', ''))
df['Sale Price'] = df['Sale Price'].apply(lambda x: x.replace(',', ''))
In [13]:
# Remove $ from retail price
df['Retail Price'] = df['Retail Price'].apply(lambda x: x.replace('$', ''))
In [14]:
# Converting some object columns into numerical columns
obj_cols = ['Sale Price','Retail Price']
for col in obj_cols:
    df[str(col)] = pd.to_numeric(df[str(col)])

# Release Date, Brand distribution, Sneaker Name, Buyer Region, Retail Price, Shoe Size analysis and plot
df_cat = ['Release Date', 'Brand','Sneaker Name','Buyer Region','Retail Price','Shoe Size', 'Bought for Retail', 'Bought for Less Than Retail','Bought for higher Than Retail']
for cat in df_cat:
    cat_num = df[str(cat)].value_counts()
    plt.figure(figsize=(24,10))
    chart = sns.barplot(x = cat_num.index, y= cat_num)
    chart.set_title("Sneakers Sales by %s" % (cat))
    plt.ylabel("Sneaker Sales")
    chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(), rotation = 90)
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(plt.MultipleLocator(1))
    plt.show(30)

In [32]:
# Analyze trend between Sales Price and Order Date
# Find average sale price per day
dts = df[['Order Date', 'Sale Price']]
uniq_ord_dates = df['Order Date'].value_counts().index.tolist()
avg_3 = []

for date in uniq_ord_dates:
    daterow = dts.loc[dts['Order Date'] == str(date)]
    avg_3.append(daterow['Sale Price'].mean())

unq_dates = pd.Series(uniq_ord_dates)
date_avgs = pd.Series(avg_3)
dateprice_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Order_date', 'Average_Price'])
dateprice_df['Order_date'] = unq_dates.sort_values(ascending = True)
dateprice_df['Average_Price'] = date_avgs

In [35]:
# Analyze trend between buyer region and sale price

brg = df[['Buyer Region', 'Sale Price']]
unq_brgs = df['Buyer Region'].value_counts().index.tolist()
avg_5 = []

for region in unq_brgs:
    regionrow = brg.loc[brg['Buyer Region'] == str(region)]
    avg_5.append(regionrow['Sale Price'].mean())

unq_regions = pd.Series(unq_brgs)
region_avgs = pd.Series(avg_5)
regionprice_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Buyer Region', 'Average Price'])
regionprice_df['Buyer Region'] = unq_regions.sort_values(ascending = True)
regionprice_df['Average Price'] = region_avgs

fig_dims = (11, 10)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_dims)
chart = sns.barplot(x="Average Price", y="Buyer Region", data=regionprice_df, color="b")
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(plt.MultipleLocator(20))
chart.set_title("Average Sale Price by Buyer Region")

4. Conclusion¶

Now we know a little about the price fluctuation about several sneakers, which will help you to buy your favorite sneakers in suitable price or sell your sneakers to get more profit.¶

This project is only small part of sales of sneakers from the Stockx, there will be too many sneakers transaction in future, hopefully every body can get their favorite sneakers with suitable price.¶

if you want to see more, please follow the pages in Github.¶

5. Learning Process¶

For this project , I have apply some techniques which I learnd in the data mining class, from the pre processing data and analyzing the data to get relationship among order date, sale price and retail price. These data are so clearly and correctly show us the fluctuation of the sneakers market. Hopefully this project can help you to get some useful information about the sneakers.¶
